title: Part 9
content:
Part 9

AT SOME POINT, the fourth-generation students disappeared, leaving only two people in the room—me and Shiro.

Several months had passed since it became just the two of us.

During that time, there wasn't a single conversation; every day was silent.

However, I didn't mind; I even thought it was comfortable.

With Yuki's chatter gone, I could focus more on my studies.

Today was our first time doing judo in several days.

Due to an increase in curriculums, specific sports only came around every few days.

Still, both Shiro and I were honing our skills. Although the sports were different, the results of our training allowed us to master and apply techniques to a variety of martial arts.

"You two, do the randori together like usual. I'll step out for a bit."

The instructor acting as referee hurriedly left the room, seemingly called away.

Left behind, we started the randori as instructed, gripping each other's judo uniforms. Shiro and I had repeated this countless times.

"Can I say something?"

Part 233

It was Shiro, whispering in my ear, who broke the last few months' silence.

I thought it was a psychological attack, but he completely stopped moving.

"It's been years since I last won against you in judo, hasn't it?"

"That's right."

Since my initial defeat, I continued to win every single match.

"Boxing, karate, Jeet Kune Do—everything. The first one or two matches go to me, but once you turn it around, I can't do anything. You're really amazing."

Why would he say such a thing in the middle of a randori?

"There's something I want to tell you."

"…What?"

I listened to his whispers, which he continued at a close distance, unnoticed by the adults.

"I've decided to leave this facility."

"Only those who drop out can leave here."

"That's why I'm going to drop out voluntarily. Watching the adults chase after the dropouts' tendencies and responses, I can imagine what kind of path they all take. At least I won't be killed."

"What will you do in the outside world? Is there any meaning to that?"

"There is. I want freedom."

"Freedom?"

"I want to be free. I want friends. Isn't it normal to have such feelings? Look around. Only you and I are left, Kiyotaka. This situation will continue for over ten more years."

I didn't understand what Shiro meant.

Why does he want such things?

"Aren't you interested in the outside world? Or, can you really endure this pain?"

"I've never harbored such interest or doubts."

"A unilaterally provided education, this confined space—are you really satisfied with that?"

"At least, I'm not dissatisfied."

In my days of learning in the White Room, I was definitely growing.

Isn't it natural to want to know how far you can grow?

In the outside world, this education wouldn't be available, meaning the efficiency in which I improved would decrease.

"…You're strange. I want to see the real world, not a virtual one."

Objectively speaking, I understood that many children grew weary of a life of continuous restraint and confinement. However, I had never considered dropping out due to an inability to endure.

"When Yuki dropped out, I became sure of it. I even felt envious watching her."

"I see."

If this was Shiro's conclusion, there was nothing for me to add.

"I thought you were the same. I thought you must've wanted to go outside someday."

"Sorry, but I've never thought that."

"…I see. I was going to invite you to go out together, but…"

The adults monitoring us probably didn't know about these thoughts, just like me.

They wouldn't know that Shiro harbored various feelings towards this facility.

There was an established notion that the children couldn't know what they weren't taught. However, in reality, I discovered that there were people, just like the person in front of me, who wanted to leave the White Room immediately.

Now that I've become the last one left, I don't know how significant this discovery is.

"I'll go ahead. Let's meet again someday, Kiyotaka."

I didn't respond to those words.

I only felt his extraordinary determination. Moreover, I felt a fighting spirit I had never felt before, a spirit to defeat me in this battle. The opponent in front of me wasn't an easy one, more so than defeating half-hearted adults. Yet—

"Ugh!"

I dodged Shiro's attack and scored a clean hit.

Since we had learned the same way, there was no way I'd lose.

If the opponent exerted 120% effort, I would exert 130%.

If the opponent exerted 140% effort, I would exert 150%.

Whether the White Room was comfortable, what freedom was like—none of that mattered.

There were still many things to learn here. That was what mattered.

This wasn't something you should avoid in the pursuit of self-improvement.

It was as if my intellectual curiosity was telling me to stay in the White Room.

"Until then!"

Even though there was no referee nearby, we were always being watched from a separate room on the second floor, beyond the glass.

I slammed Shiro onto the tatami, and it was understood that the match had been decided.

"In the end… I lost again, huh? I should've remembered more about the times I won."

Leaning an arm on his forehead, he gasped for breath and spoke of faded memories.

"It's been five years of constant losing. I've realized that I can't win even if I stay here…"

"Are you really planning to drop out?"

"Yeah. I'll leave the White Room when the time comes."

He seemed to have no intention of changing his mind.

I couldn't understand. Dropping out of the White Room was death, no matter the form.

I couldn't think of willingly dying.

But Shiro must have had his own feelings.

If he intended to take his own life, I wouldn't stop him.

"Goodbye, Shiro."

"Goodbye, Kiyotaka."

That was the last conversation between me and Shiro.
